#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:13
msgid "Package parameters and overrides with `callPackage`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:15
msgid ""
"Nix ships with a special-purpose programming language for creating packages "
"and configurations: the Nix language. It is used to build the Nix package "
"collection, known as {term}`Nixpkgs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:18
msgid ""
"Being purely functional, the Nix language allows declaring custom functions "
"to abstract over common patterns. One of the most prominent patterns in "
"Nixpkgs is parametrisation of package recipes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:21
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:23
msgid ""
"Nixpkgs is a sizeable software project on its own, with coding conventions "
"and idioms that have emerged over the years. It has [established a "
"convention](https://github.com/nixos/nixpkgs/commit/"
"d17f0f9cbca38fabb71624f069cd4c0d6feace92) of composing parameterised "
"packages with automatic settings through a function named [`callPackage`]"
"(https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/commit/"
"fd268b4852d39c18e604c584dd49a611dc795a9b). This tutorial shows how to use it "
"and why it's beneficial."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:27
msgid "What will you learn?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:29
msgid ""
"Using `callPackage` to invoke package recipes that follow Nixpkgs conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:30
msgid "Overriding package parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:31
msgid "Creating interdependent package sets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:33
msgid "What do you need?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:35
msgid "Familiarity with the [Nix language](reading-nix-language)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:36
msgid "First experience with [packaging existing software](packaging-tutorial)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:38
msgid "How long does it take?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:40
msgid "45 minutes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:42
msgid "Automatic function calls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:44
msgid ""
"Create a new file `hello.nix`, which could be a typical package recipe as "
"found in Nixpkgs: A function that takes an attribute set, with attributes "
"corresponding to derivations in the top-level package set, and returns a "
"derivation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:47 ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:111
msgid "hello.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:47
msgid ""
"{ writeShellScriptBin }:\n"
"writeShellScriptBin \"hello\" ''\n"
"  echo \"Hello, world!\"\n"
"''"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:0
msgid "Detailed explanation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:56
msgid ""
"`hello.nix` declares a function which takes as argument an attribute set "
"with one element `writeShellScriptBin`. [`writeShellScriptBin`](https://"
"nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/unstable/#trivial-builder-writeShellScriptBin) is a "
"function that happens to exist in Nixpkgs, a [build helper](https://nixos."
"org/manual/nixpkgs/unstable/#part-builders) that returns a derivation. The "
"derivation output in this case contains an executable shell script in `$out/"
"bin/hello` that prints \"Hello world\" when run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:61
msgid "Now create a file `default.nix` with the following contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:63 ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:91
#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:127 ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:160
#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:203 ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:229
msgid "default.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:63
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
"in\n"
"pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:71
msgid ""
"Realise the derivation in `default.nix` and run the executable that is "
"produced:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:73
msgid ""
"$ nix-build\n"
"$ ./result/bin/hello\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:79
msgid ""
"The argument `writeShellScriptBin` gets filled in automatically when the "
"function in `hello.nix` is evaluated. For every attribute in the function's "
"argument, `callPackage` passes an attribute from the `pkgs` attribute set if "
"it exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:82
msgid ""
"It may appear cumbersome to create the extra file `hello.nix` for the "
"package in such a simple setup. We have done so because this is exactly how "
"Nixpkgs is organised: Every package recipe is a file that declares a "
"function. This function takes as arguments the package's dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:87
msgid "Parameterised builds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:89
msgid ""
"Change the `default.nix` to produce an attribute set of derivations, with "
"the attribute `hello` containing the original derivation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:91
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { };\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:101
msgid ""
"When building the attribute `hello`, by accessing it with the [`-A` / `--"
"attr` option](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/2.19/command-ref/nix-build#opt-"
"attr), the result will be the same as before:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:103
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A hello\n"
"$ ./result/bin/hello\n"
"Hello, world!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:109
msgid ""
"Also change `hello.nix` to add an additional parameter `audience` with "
"default value `\"world\"`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:111
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  writeShellScriptBin,\n"
"  audience ? \"world\",\n"
"}:\n"
"writeShellScriptBin \"hello\" ''\n"
"  echo \"Hello, ${audience}!\"\n"
"''"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:122
msgid "This also does not change the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:124
msgid ""
"Things get more interesting when changing `default.nix` to make use of this "
"new argument. Pass the parameter `audience` in the second argument to "
"`callPackage`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:127
msgid ""
" let\n"
"   pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
" in\n"
" {\n"
"-  hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { };\n"
"+  hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { audience = \"people\"; };\n"
" }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:138
msgid ""
"This attribute is passed on to the argument of the function defined in "
"`hello.nix`: The same syntax can also be used to explicitly set the "
"automatically discovered arguments, such as `writeShellScriptBin`, but that "
"doesn't make sense here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:141
msgid "Try it out:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:143
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A hello\n"
"$ ./result/bin/hello\n"
"Hello, people!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:149
msgid ""
"This pattern is used widely in Nixpkgs: For example, functions which "
"represent Go programs often have a parameter `buildGoModule`. It is common "
"to find expressions like `callPackage ./go-program.nix { buildGoModule = "
"buildGo116Module; }` to change the default Go compiler version. Nixpkgs is "
"therefore not simply a huge library of pre-configured packages, but a "
"collection of functions – package *recipes* – for customising packages and "
"even entire ecosystems (for example \"All Python packages using my custom "
"interpreter\") on the fly without duplicating code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:154
msgid "Overrides"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:156
msgid ""
"`callPackage` adds more convenience by allowing parameters to be customised "
"_after the fact_ using the returned derivation's `override` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:158
msgid ""
"Add a third attribute `hello-folks` to `default.nix` and set it to `hello."
"override` called with a new value for `audience`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:160
msgid ""
" let\n"
"   pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
" in\n"
"-{\n"
"+rec {\n"
"   hello = pkgs.callPackage ./hello.nix { audience = \"people\"; };\n"
"+  hello-folks = hello.override { audience = \"folks\"; };\n"
" }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:173
msgid ""
"The resulting attribute set is now recursive (by the keyword `rec`). That "
"is, attribute values can refer to names from within the same attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:177
msgid ""
"`override` passes `audience` to the original function in `hello.nix` - it "
"*overrides* whatever arguments have been passed in the original "
"`callPackage` that produced the derivation `hello`. All the other parameters "
"will remain the same. This is especially useful and can be often found on "
"packages that provide many options to customise a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:181
msgid ""
"Building `hello-folks` attribute and running the resulting executable will "
"again produce a new version of the script:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:183
msgid ""
"$ nix-build -A hello-folks\n"
"$ ./result/bin/hello\n"
"Hello, folks!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:189
msgid ""
"A real-world example is the [`neovim`](https://search.nixos.org/packages?"
"show=neovim) package recipe, which has overridable arguments such as "
"`extraLuaPackages`, `extraPythonPackages`, or `withRuby`. Currently these "
"parameters are only discoverable by reading the source code, which can be "
"found by following the link to 📦 Source on [search.nixos.org/packages]"
"(https://search.nixos.org/packages)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:192
msgid "Interdependent package sets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:194
msgid ""
"You can actually create your own version of `callPackage`! This comes in "
"handy for package sets where the recipes depend on each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:198
msgid ""
"The following examples do not show the \"called\" files, as they are not "
"necessary for understanding the principle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:201
msgid "Consider the following recursive attribute set of derivations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:203
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
"in\n"
"rec {\n"
"  a = pkgs.callPackage ./a.nix { };\n"
"  b = pkgs.callPackage ./b.nix { inherit a; };\n"
"  c = pkgs.callPackage ./c.nix { inherit b; };\n"
"  d = pkgs.callPackage ./d.nix { };\n"
"  e = pkgs.callPackage ./e.nix { inherit c d; };\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:218
msgid "Here, `inherit a;` is equivalent to `a = a;`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:221
msgid ""
"Previously declared derivations are passed as arguments to other derivations "
"through `callPackage`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:223
msgid ""
"In this case you have to remember to manually specify all arguments required "
"by each package in the respective {term}`Nix file` that are not in Nixpkgs. "
"If `./b.nix` requires an argument `a` but there is no `pkgs.a`, the function "
"call will produce an error. This can become quite tedious quickly, "
"especially for larger package sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:227
msgid ""
"Use `lib.callPackageWith` to create your own `callPackage` based on an "
"attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:229
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
"  callPackage = pkgs.lib.callPackageWith (pkgs // packages);\n"
"  packages = {\n"
"    a = callPackage ./a.nix { };\n"
"    b = callPackage ./b.nix { };\n"
"    c = callPackage ./c.nix { };\n"
"    d = callPackage ./d.nix { };\n"
"    e = callPackage ./e.nix { };\n"
"  };\n"
"in\n"
"packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:245
msgid "This requires some explanation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:247
msgid ""
"First of all note that instead of a recursive attribute set, the names we "
"operate on are now assigned in a `let` binding. It has the same property as "
"recursive sets: Names on the left can be used in expressions on the right of "
"the equal sign (`=`). This is how we can refer to `packages` when we merge "
"its contents with the pre-existing attribute set `pkgs` using the `//` "
"operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:252
msgid ""
"Your custom `callPackages` now makes available all the attributes in `pkgs` "
"*and* `packages` to the called package function (the same names from "
"`packages` taking precedence), and `packages` is being built up recursively "
"with each call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:254
msgid ""
"The last bit may make your head spin. This construction is only possible "
"because the Nix language is lazily evaluated. That is, values are only "
"computed when they are actually needed. It allows passing `packages` around "
"without having fully defined it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:259
msgid ""
"Each package's dependencies are now implicit at this level (they are still "
"explicit in each of the package files), and `callPackage` resolves them "
"*automagically*. This relieves you from dealing with them manually, and "
"precludes configuration errors that may only surface late into a lengthy "
"build process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/callpackage.md:262
msgid ""
"Of course this small example is still manageable in the original form. And "
"the implicitly recursive variant can obscure the structure for software "
"developers not familiar with lazy evaluation, making it harder to read for "
"them than it was before. But this benefit really pays off for large "
"constructions, where it is the amount of code that would obscure the "
"structure, and where manual modifications would become cumbersome and error-"
"prone."
msgstr ""

